[1] Comment re vaccination post in ProMED-mail Ebola update (124): Sierra Leone, Eurosurveillance, Suspected, Research, Vaccine 20151108.3776823 by AJ Kucharski et al.

ProMED thanks Dr. Kucharski for submitting a response to the ProMED post of the news report on the ring vaccination modeling study [See ProMED mail Ebola update (124): Sierra Leone, Eurosurveillance, Suspected, Research, Vaccine 20151108.3776823 items 3 and 4] to be published in 2016: Kucharski AJ, Eggo RM, Watson CH, Camacho A, Funk S, Edmunds WJ. Effectiveness of ring vaccination as control strategy for Ebola virus disease. Emerg Infect Dis. 2016 Jan [date cited]. http://dx.doi.org/10.3201/eid2201.151410. The abstract from the new EID publication and the authors' comment follow with a response from ProMED Mod.JW.

Abstract: Using an Ebola virus disease transmission model, we found that addition of ring vaccination at the outset of the West Africa epidemic might not have led to containment of this disease. However, in later stages of the epidemic or outbreaks with less intense transmission or more effective control, this strategy could help eliminate the disease.

Comment from the authors:

We were surprised that ProMED chose to circulate a clearly erroneous summary of our Ebola ring vaccination modelling study from a news website rather than circulating a link to the paper itself: http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/22/1/15-1410_article.[1]

VaccineNewsDaily.com's report, repeated on ProMED, stated that our study "found using ring vaccination at the beginning of the outbreak did not help to contain the virus. However, when the outbreak had decreased to a less-intense [sic] transmission rate, it helped eliminate the disease". Not only does this suggest that vaccine was in use at the start of the West African epidemic--which it was not--it misrepresents the methods and results of our study. Our mathematical model examined the effect of ring vaccination on Ebola transmission dynamics in a range of scenarios, including 1 in which case ascertainment was incomplete and missed cases result in large secondary clusters, based on published field data from 2014.[2,3] Our analysis found that under such circumstances outbreaks might not be contained with ring vaccination alone, though ring vaccination would still reduce overall transmission and case counts.

The interim findings of the Ebola ça Suffit rVSV vaccine cluster randomised trial [4] (in which co-authors CHW, AC and WJE are co-investigators) provide strong evidence that ring vaccination can have an important role in the control of Ebola virus disease. Indeed, a secondary outcome from the trial suggests the vaccine gives indirect protection to unvaccinated cluster members, which points to the potential role that ring vaccination can play as a containment measure. Our paper attempted to extend and generalise these findings by modelling a range of different scenarios. The results suggest that ring vaccination requires effective public health systems to deliver its full potential, including capacity for timely case ascertainment and response. If such capacity is insufficient or unavailable, then other vaccination strategies for Ebola control may need to be considered -- such as the hybrid ring and mass vaccination approaches used successfully against smallpox.[5].

Adam J. Kucharski, Rosalind M. Eggo, Conall H. Watson, Anton Camacho, Sebastian Funk, W. John Edmunds
1. Kucharski AJ, Eggo RM, Watson CH, Camacho A, Funk S, et al. (2016) Effectiveness of Ring Vaccination as Control Strategy for Ebola Virus Disease. Emerg Infect Dis J 22. http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/22/1/15-1410.
2. Faye O, Boëlle P-Y, Heleze E, Faye O, Loucoubar C, et al. (2015) Chains of transmission and control of Ebola virus disease in Conakry, Guinea, in 2014: an observational study. Lancet Infect Dis. Available: http://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(14)71075-8/abstract.
3. Althaus CL (2015) Ebola superspreading. Lancet Infect Dis 15: 507-508. http://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(15)70135-0/abstract.
4. Henao-Restrepo AM, Longini IM, Egger M, Dean NE, Edmunds WJ, et al. (2015) Efficacy and effectiveness of an rVSV-vectored vaccine expressing Ebola surface glycoprotein: interim results from the Guinea ring vaccination cluster-randomised trial. Lancet 9996: 857-866. http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0140673615611175.
5. Fenner F, Henderson DA, Arita I, Jezek Z, Ladnyi ID (1988) Smallpox and Its Eradication. Geneva: World Health Organization.

