Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED thanks Dr Kucharski for this clarification, but I disagree that the media report gives the impression that vaccination was available at the start of the epidemic. It is quite clear that the original report, available at http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/22/1/15-1410_article, is a model, and the media report quoted the abstract from that almost verbatim. The abstract states that "we found that addition of ring vaccination at the outset of the West Africa epidemic ***might not*** have led to containment of this disease." [see above]. Furthermore, there are many caveats in the text of the article about the conditions necessary for the success of ring vaccination, none of which were met at the start of the epidemic. - Mod.JW]

*******
[2] Suspected cases
12 Nov 2015 Australia: Australian government scaling back Ebola screening at airports http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2015-11/12/c_134807992.htm
[According to government authorities in a statement on Thurs (12 Nov 2015), travelers from Ebola-affected countries will still be assessed through standard screening protocols, but passengers will no longer be required to complete an Ebola travel history card or have their temperature checked. According to the WHO (World Health Organization) in its weekly Ebola situation report on Wed 11 Nov 2015, "The country has now entered a 90-day period of enhanced surveillance, which is scheduled to conclude on 5 Feb 2016, which includes a rapid reporting and detection system in unaffected areas."]

12 Nov 2015 Brazil: Ebola scare in Brazil: Traveler tested for disease after visiting West African country
http://www.latintimes.com/ebola-scare-brazil-traveler-tested-disease-after-visiting-west-african-country-352897
[The traveler tested negative for Ebola virus disease, positive for malaria. - Mod.LK]
Also see:
14 Nov 2015 Brazil: Brazilian tests negative for Ebola virus a 2nd time
http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/health/2015/11/14/brazilian-tests-negative-for-ebola-virus-second-time/
[According to Brazil's Health Ministry who spoke on Sat 14 Nov 2015, a man who began experiencing symptoms similar to that of Ebola virus disease (EVD) after returning from a trip to Guinea, has tested negative a 2nd time for EVD.]

14 Nov 2015 Ghana: Parliament has approved Ebola vaccine trials in the country and urged the Minister of Health to intensify education on the clinical trials.
http://graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/53411-parliament-approves-ebola-vaccine-trials-in-the-country.html
[On 11 Jun 2015, Ghana suspended the planned Ebola virus disease (EVD) vaccine trial secondary to local protests and concerns about the safety of Guineans participating in the trials.
According to an article published on 14 Nov 2015, after reviewing the issue, Parliament has now approved Ebola vaccine trials in the country and urged the Minister of Health to increase education efforts for the clinical trials. The Health Committee of Parliament, which considered the report, also resolved to undertake reviews on all the processes involved in the clinical trials. Cameron, Mali, Nigeria and Senegal are the other 4 countries participating in the trials.]

14 Nov 2015: Guinea releases last 68 people from Ebola quarantine
http://goo.gl/ypm76U
[According to Dr. Abdourahmane Bathily, head of the Ebola center in Forecariah (western Guinea), the last of the 68 people who were in contact with a patient with Ebola virus disease (EVD) were released from quarantine on Sat 14 Nov 2015. Dr. Bathily also said the last confirmed EVD case was a baby in isolation, who should be released from a treatment center next week. This will allow Guinea to begin its 42-day countdown for declaration of the end of EVD.]

11 Nov 2015 Guinea goes a week with no new Ebola detections
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2015/11/guinea-goes-week-no-new-ebola-detection
[Guinea reported no Ebola cases last week, a period of high alert, given that the most recent cluster of family-linked cases generated several risky exposures, the World Health Organization (WHO) said today [11 Nov 2015].
Looking at the bigger picture, the number of cases in Guinea has stayed at 4 or fewer for the past 16 weeks, the WHO noted in its weekly snapshot of the outbreak.]
[Very promising news! - Mod.LK]

12 Nov 2015 Liberia: Officially closing the Ebola Treatment Unit in Sinje
http://liberia.iom.int/2015/11/12/officially-closing-the-ebola-treatment-unit-in-grand-cape-mount/
[The Grand Cape Mount County Health Team (CHT), Superintendent, traditional and religious leaders, Ebola survivors, community members, USAID-OFDA and Institute of Medicine (IOM) staff officially marked the closing of the Sinje Ebola Treatment Unit (ETU).]

13 Nov 2015 Liberia: Exxon Mobil to drill offshore post-Ebola Liberia
http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/11/13/liberia-oil-idUKL8N1376WU20151113?rpc=401
[According to President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf, the commitment by Exxon Mobil to drill in Liberia is a sign of economic recovery after the Ebola virus disease (EVD) epidemic.]

15 Nov 2015 Sierra Leone: Airtel adopts 50 Ebola orphans
http://www.sierraexpressmedia.com/?p=76453
[Airtel Sierra Leone, a mobile communication company, has adopted 50 Ebola-affected orphans in Sierra Leone. The children will be cared for by the SOS Children Villages in Freetown, Bo and Makeni. An estimated 5000 children have lost their parents during the Ebola outbreak, and they are at risk for not reaching their full potential unless people step in to help.]

11 Nov 2015 UK: Ebola victim ["PC"] wins latest health battle
http://goo.gl/fkmlQG
[UK's (United Kingdom's) "Ebola nurse," PC was first hospitalized for the Ebola virus disease (EVD) contracted in Sierra Leone in late-December 2014 and discharged "Ebola free" from
Royal Free Hospital London (RFHL) in late-January 2015. She had issues with post-Ebola disorders following discharge, but was free from active EVD until 9 Oct 2015 when she was again admitted to RFHL for a resurgence of the original EVD infection (which was not known to be possible before) with the development of meningitis from the residual virus in her brain. In hospital, she had a rocky course, being declared critically ill at one point.
RFHL announced today that she is no longer in isolation, is not infectious, and had been discharged from its care and transferred to Glasgow's Queen Elizabeth University Hospital to continue her recovery. Quoting PC: "I am forever thankful for the amazing care I have received at the Royal Free Hospital. I am looking forward to returning to Scotland and to seeing my family and friends again. For a 2nd time, staff across many departments of the hospital have worked incredibly hard to help me recover and I will always be grateful to them and the NHS."]

[And we at ProMED wish this amazing individual well. We are hoping for a full recovery. She is truly a survivor! - Mod.LK]

13 Nov 2015 UK: Britain ends military support for Ebola fight in West Africa
http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Security-Industry/2015/11/13/Britain-ends-military-support-for-Ebola-fight-in-West-Africa/4231447438292/?spt=sec&or=bn
[The last 8 military personnel returned home to the UK, ending the UK's military involvement in the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak.]

Rhein BA, et al. (12 Nov 2015) Interferon-gamma Inhibits Ebola virus Infection. PubMed.gov, 11(11):e1005263. doi: 0.1371/journal.ppat.1005263. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26562011
[Findings of the study suggest interferon gamma, an FDA-approved drug, may serve as a novel and effective prophylactic or treatment option.]

13 Nov 2015 UK: Imperial War Museum to put objects from British military campaigns against Ebola and ISIS on public display
http://www.culture24.org.uk/history-and-heritage/military-history/art541251-ebola-isis-exhibition-imperial-war-museum-london
[With boots, targets and tornadoes, Imperial War Museum London is about to host the 1st exhibition looking at the experiences of British forces responding to the Ebola outbreak in Sierra Leone.]

